<div class="row g-4"><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W"><h2 id="measuring-biodiversity-within-a-habitat">Measuring Biodiversity Within a Habitat</h2><ul><li><p>The place where an organism lives is called its <b>habitat</b></p></li><li><p>Habitats can vary in size, with some being very large (e.g. grasslands) while others are very small (e.g. a puddle of water that formed after heavy rain)</p></li><li><p>Measuring the <b>species diversity</b> within different habitats can be useful in making comparisons between them or when studying how habitats change over time</p></li><li><p>One way to determine species diversity is to measure <b>species richness</b> in a habitat</p></li><li><p><b>Species richness</b> is the <b>number</b> of species within a community</p><ul><li><p>A community is a group of populations of <b>different species</b> living in the same place at the same time that <b>interact with each other</b></p></li></ul></li><li><p>Species richness is the simplest way to measure <b>species diversity</b></p></li><li><p>A community with a greater number of species will have a greater species richness score</p><ul><li><p>For example, a tropical rain forest has a very high number of different species so it would be described as <b>species-rich</b></p></li></ul></li><li><p>Species richness can be a <b>misleading</b> indicator of diversity as it does not take into account the <b>number of individuals</b> of each species</p></li><li><p><b>Species abundance</b> is a measure of the <b>relative number of individuals</b> in the different species within a given area</p><ul><li><p>In the example below, Area 1 and Area 2 both contain 4 tree species</p></li><li><p>However, Area 2 is actually <b>dominated</b> by one species and in fact, one of the species is very <b>rare</b> (only one individual)</p></li><li><p>Although the two areas have exactly the same <b>species richness</b>, Area 1 has a <b>higher species abundance</b> (and therefore a <b>higher overall species diversity</b>) than Area 2</p></li><li><p>This example illustrates the limitations of using just species richness on its own</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Conservationists often favour the use of an <b>index of diversity</b> as it takes into account species number and evenness</p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Species richness and evenness" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="591" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Species-richness-and-evenness.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/06/Species-richness-and-evenness.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/06/Species-richness-and-evenness.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/06/Species-richness-and-evenness.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/06/Species-richness-and-evenness.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/06/Species-richness-and-evenness.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/06/Species-richness-and-evenness.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/06/Species-richness-and-evenness.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/06/Species-richness-and-evenness.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/06/Species-richness-and-evenness.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/06/Species-richness-and-evenness.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/06/Species-richness-and-evenness.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/06/Species-richness-and-evenness.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/06/Species-richness-and-evenness.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/06/Species-richness-and-evenness.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/06/Species-richness-and-evenness.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/06/Species-richness-and-evenness.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Area 1 and 2 have the same species richness but different species abundance. Area 1 will have a higher overall species diversity as it has a higher species abundance. Species diversity takes both richness and abundance into account.</b></i></p><ul><li><p>Measuring the different levels of biodiversity within an ecosystem can be challenging</p></li><li><p>Finding out which species live in an ecosystem and the size of the populations requires the <b>identification and cataloguing</b> of all organisms present to build a <b>species list</b></p></li><li><p>This is possible for areas that are very small or where the species are very large like trees</p></li><li><p>However, for larger and more complex ecosystems like rainforests, it is simply <b>impossible </b>to find, identify and count every organism that exists there</p></li><li><p>When this is the case, different<b> samples </b>of the area can be taken and used to make an <b>estimate for the total</b> species numbers in the area</p></li></ul><h4 id="random-sampling">Random sampling</h4><ul><li><p>Some ecosystems are very complex with large numbers of different species of different sizes</p></li><li><p>For the sake of logistics, <b>random</b> <b>sampling</b> is often used to estimate the <b>distribution</b> and <b>abundance</b> of species</p><ul><li><p>The <b>distribution</b> of a species describes how it is spread throughout the ecosystem</p></li><li><p>The <b>abundance</b> of a species is the number of individuals of that species</p></li></ul></li><li><p>When carrying out sampling, square frames called <b>quadrats</b> can be used to mark off the area being sampled</p><ul><li><p>Quadrats are square frames made of wood or wire</p></li><li><p>They can be a variety of sizes eg. 0.25m<sup>2</sup> or 1m<sup>2</sup></p></li><li><p>They are placed on the ground and the organisms within them are recorded</p></li><li><p>They can be used to measure the distribution and abundance of <b>plants</b> </p></li></ul></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Quadrat in use" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="683" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Quadrat-in-use.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/07/Quadrat-in-use.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Using a quadrat to investigate population size or distribution</b></i></p><ul><li><p>Quadrats of different sizes can be used depending on what is being measured and what is most suitable in the space the samples are being made in</p></li><li><p>Quadrats must be laid <b>randomly</b> in the area to <b>avoid </b><span class="popovers" data-content="When a sample is collected in such a way that some members of the intended population are more or less likely to be included than others. The data you collect may therefore not be accurate or represent the group." data-title="Sampling Bias" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition"><b>sampling bias</b></span></p><ul><li><p>This random sampling can be done by converting the sampling area into a <b>grid format </b>and labelling each square on the grid with a number</p></li><li><p>Then a random number generator is used to pick the sample points</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Once the quadrat has been laid on the chosen sample point the <b>abundance</b> or <b>percentage cover</b> of all the <b>different</b> <b>species</b> present can be recorded</p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Percentage Cover in Quadrat" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="733" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Percentage-Cover-in-Quadrat.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Using a quadrat to investigate the percentage cover of two species of grass. Some squares may be lacking any species while other squares may have multiple species in them - this means that the total percentage cover may sometimes be over or under 100%</b></i></p><ul><li><p>Quadrats are suitable for sampling <b>plants</b> </p></li><li><p>For many <b>animal species</b>, however, it is not possible to use quadrats to measure their distribution and abundance</p></li><li><p>In these cases, <b>other techniques</b> involving other items of <b>equipment</b> are necessary, including:</p><ul><li><p><b>Sweeping nets</b>: these are large, strong nets with a fine material (very small holes) that are used to catch flying insects and insects that live in long grass by sweeping the net back and forth through the grass</p></li><li><p><b>Pitfall traps</b>: these are cans or jars that are buried in the ground that are used to catch ground-dwelling (often nocturnal) insects and other invertebrates as they fall into the trap</p></li><li><p><b>Kick-sampling</b>: this technique is used to catch freshwater invertebrates living in streams or rivers. A net in placed on the stream-bed so that the water is flowing into it and the stream-bed just above the net is churned up by the scientist (using their foot) for a set period of time. The invertebrates are carried by the stream into the net</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Take as <b>many samples</b> as possible to get a more accurate indication of the entire habitat</p></li><li><p>The results can be used to <b>estimate</b> the total number of individuals or species richness in the habitat</p></li><li><p>It is important to use the <b>same sampling method</b> when gathering data to compare different habitats with one another</p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Invertebrate sampling techniques (1)" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="797" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-1.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-1.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-1.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-1.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-1.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-1.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-1.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-1.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-1.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-1.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-1.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-1.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-1.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-1.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-1.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-1.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-1.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Example of how a pitfall trap can be used</b></i></p><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Invertebrate sampling techniques (4)" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="708" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-4.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-4.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-4.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-4.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-4.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-4.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-4.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-4.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-4.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-4.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-4.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-4.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-4.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-4.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-4.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-4.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/05/Invertebrate-sampling-techniques-4.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Example of how kick-sampling is done</b></i></p><h4 id="measuring-genetic-diversity-within-a-species">Measuring genetic diversity within a species</h4><ul><li><p>Genetic diversity refers to the <b>different alleles</b> that occur within the <span class="popovers" data-content="All the different alleles of all the genes of all the individuals in a population at any one time." data-title="Gene pool" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">gene pool</span> of a species or a population</p></li><li><p>The <b>greater</b> the allele variety within a species, the <b>higher</b> the genetic diversity will be</p></li><li><p>Measurements of genetic diversity is useful to investigate changes occurring in a population over time or when comparing two species with one another</p></li><li><p>To measure genetic diversity two factors can be considered:</p><ul><li><p><b>Phenotype</b></p></li><li><p><b>Genotype</b></p></li></ul></li><li><p>The <b>phenotype</b> of an organism refers to its <b>observable features</b></p></li><li><p><b>Different alleles</b> are responsible for the <b>variety of phenotypes</b> that can be observed within a species</p></li><li><p><b>Therefore,</b> the greater the variety of phenotypes within a species, the higher the genetic diversity</p></li><li><p>An organisms <b>genotype</b> is determined by the <b>different alleles</b> that is found within the cells</p></li><li><p>Different alleles will have a different order of bases in the DNA molecules</p></li><li><p>These base orders can be determined by sequencing the DNA of individuals in a species</p></li><li><p>The <b>higher</b> the number of <b>different alleles</b> for a characteristic, the <b>greater</b> the <b>genetic diversity</b> within that species</p></li><li><p>Another way to determine the genetic diversity within a species is to use the <b>heterozygosity index</b></p></li></ul><h4 id="heterozygosity-index">Heterozygosity index</h4><ul><li><p>Organisms that have two different alleles at a particular gene <span class="popovers" data-content="The specific linear position of a particular gene on a certain chromosome." data-title="Locus" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">locus</span> are known as <b>heterozygotes</b></p></li><li><p>The <b>higher</b> the proportion of heterozygotes in a population, the <b>greater</b> the genetic diversity of that population will be</p></li><li><p>We can use the following formula to calculate the <b>heterozygosity index</b> (H):</p></li></ul><p class="text-center"><img alt="straight H space equals space fraction numerator number space of space heterozygotes over denominator number space of space individuals space in space the space population end fraction" data-mathml='&lt;math style="font-family:Arial" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant="normal"&gt;H&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt; &lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt; &lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mfrac&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;number&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt; &lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;of&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt; &lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;heterozygotes&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;number&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt; &lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;of&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt; &lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;individuals&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt; &lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;in&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt; &lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;the&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt; &lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;population&